For fields -

Field-Level Security	Determines visibility/editability of individual fields.  ( Read and edit access can be controlled on specific fields )
We can either view a field or row in table like department is visible or not.
And we can edit this department field or not - Like Computer science to Mechanical can be assigned or not.

Only Required Fields and master-detail fields on child (Always 'Required' By default.) cant be controlled on field level security in salesforce.
They are always Readable and editable.

What About Permission Sets?

Permission sets could be considered add-ons for profiles.
Profiles are basically a group which has some permissions. A user is assigned this means now whole group has access to those stuff.
But what if a user from this group needs to be given some special access. In that case we provide permission set to that user.

Profiles - Accesses of a group.
Permission Set - Special or add on access to the user assigned to a particular profile.
In order to grant a very specific ability to a user, you obviously don‚Äôt want to create a whole new profile.

+-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+

Sharing Settings:

Profiles control what a user can do in Salesforce (permissions), while Roles control what data a user can see (record visibility).

2Ô∏è‚É£	OWD (Organization-Wide Defaults)	Sets record-level access baseline. Defines how broadly records are shared by default. -- Note: It is set for all the profiles in one go. So it is organisation wide default.

Now we can control the record visibility as well in the salesforce. But why?
We want to control the security of the records the users "dont own".
OWD is a key part of Salesforce‚Äôs "record-level" security model.

Why It‚Äôs Needed:

Protect sensitive data: Prevent users from seeing or editing records they shouldn‚Äôt.

Establish minimum access: Define what the most restricted user can see or do.

Enable layered sharing: Acts as the foundation for more advanced sharing mechanisms like roles, sharing rules, and teams.

Access Level	Description:
Private	Users can only see records they own.
Public Read Only	Users can view all records but only edit their own.
Public Read/Write	Users can view and edit all records.
Controlled by Parent	Access is determined by the parent object (used for child relationships).
Can configure OWD for both standard objects (like Account, Opportunity) and custom objects.

Yes, in Salesforce, objects that are part of a Master-Detail relationship automatically have their 
Organization-Wide Defaults (OWD) set to ‚ÄúControlled by Parent".

When an object is a detail in a Master-Detail relationship:
Its record-level access is inherited from the master (parent) object.
You cannot set OWD manually for the detail object ‚Äî Salesforce disables that option.

Kyuki master pr access nai hua to child me master object ki field error degi. Ki master kaha he!

1 On Course object I gave all the access on profile to perform cred on the object so one can do all the operations on the records present.
2 Now in owd I made the access to Private on Course Object. Means I can't see other users records. Hence I cant do crud on their records.
So in 1 I can do what operations on course object is mentioned but in 2 I can do those operations on which records is mentioned.

In Public I can see others records but cant do anything else. Buttons are showing to edit but we can't.

So, basically OWD is for accessing others records.
Now I have set other can just see my records but cant do anything else on those.

But now i want to open this security a bit.
I want my manager can access these records and edit them as well. So I am going to use roles for this. 
Opening my records access vertically.

Roles ---------

Think of roles as vertical access control: They determine who can see data owned by whom.
They work in tandem with OWD (Organization-Wide Defaults) to open up access upward in the hierarchy.

CEO
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ VP of Sales
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Regional Manager
        ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Sales Rep

If OWD is Private, a Sales Rep can only see their own records.
But the Regional Manager, VP, and CEO can see the Sales Rep‚Äôs records because they are higher in the role hierarchy.

By default the ones above in the heirarchy, can see, edit and delete the records of the
ones below them in the case when the OWD of that object is set to private. Not the ones in parallel.
They cant see the records of someone in parallel.

----------------------------------------------------+ Understood roles now

Now if I wish to open my records horizontally.

4Ô∏è‚É£	Sharing Rules	Opens access horizontally (peer-level sharing). Refines OWD for specific conditions.

Sharing Rules are automated rules that grant additional access to records based on:

(Types)
a. Who owns the record (owner-based sharing) -- Share all records owned by ‚ÄúSales Reps‚Äù with ‚ÄúSales Managers‚Äù
b. What the record contains (criteria-based sharing) -- Share all Accounts where Industry = Healthcare with ‚ÄúHealthcare Team‚Äù

Why Use Sharing Rules?

a. OWD sets the baseline (e.g., Private), but Sharing Rules let you open up access.
b. They‚Äôre essential when users need access to records they don‚Äôt own.
c. You can share with roles, public groups, or territories.


On same page : Sharing settings 

We have option to create a sharing rule.

üß± Example Use Case
You set Case OWD to Private. You create a criteria-based sharing rule to share all Cases with Priority = High to the Support Escalation Team.

Went to sharing settings page having both OWD and Sharing rules:
Added a new rule on Owner based sharing.
